[[Category:Https://ja.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=]][[Category:New pages]][[category:original pages]][[Category:New pages]][[category:original pages]][[Category:newer pages]][[Category:newer pages]][[ja:%E5%80%AD%E5%A7%AB%E5%91%BD%E4%B8%96%E8%A8%98]]

{{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto Seiki|en}}
'''Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki''' (倭姫命世記) is a text believed to have been compiled during the [[Kamakura period]].

Within *Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki*, the work is attributed to "Negi Satsuki Maro" in Jingo Keiun 2 (768), but it is considered to have actually been compiled in the mid-Kamakura period<ref name="#1">[https://kotobank.jp/word/倭姫命世記-649457 Kotobank]</ref>. As one of the "[[Shintō Gobusho]]" (*Five Books of Shintō*), a set of scriptures for [[Ise Shintō]], the text records the journey of [[Yamato-hime no Mikoto]], a princess of Emperor Suinin as described in the *[[Kojiki]]* and *[[Nihon Shoki]]*, accompanying [[Amaterasu Ōmikami]] to her enshrinement in Ise<ref>[https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/detail/54.html *Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki*, "Rare Wahon Digital Library"]</ref><ref name="#1"/>. It also clearly asserts the doctrines of Ise Shintō<ref name="Ōsumi, 1977, p. 367">Ōsumi Kazuo, *Chūsei Shintōron*, Iwanami Shoten (1977), p. 367</ref>.

== Formation ==
The legends in *Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki* are believed to relate to the spread of *mikuriya* (imperial estates) of [[Ise Jingū]] across various regions starting in the late [[Heian period]] and the dissemination of Ise beliefs by lower-ranking priests called *oshi* during the [[Muromachi period]]<ref name="#2">[https://www.bunka.pref.mie.lg.jp/saiku/hyakuwa/journal.asp?record=23 Saiku Historical Museum, Episode 23: "Isn't It Sinful? Yamato-hime no Mikoto Seiki"]</ref>. While Kubota Osamu suggested that the text was compiled by [[Watarai Yukitada]], Kamata Jun'ichi estimated its formation occurred even before Yukitada's time<ref name="Ban, 1993, p. 5–6">Ban Isorō, "Introduction," *Shintō Taikei: Ise Shintō (Vol. 1)*, Shintō Taikei Compilation Society (1993), pp. 5–6</ref>. Among the medieval *Shintō Gobusho*, this text is considered the second oldest, following *Hōkibonki*, and is thought to have developed its ideas further<ref name="Itō, 2012, p. 99">Itō Satoshi, *Shintō to wa Nani ka*, Chūō Kōron Shinsha (2012), p. 99</ref><ref name="Ōsumi, 1977, p. 368">Ōsumi Kazuo, *Chūsei Shintōron*, Iwanami Shoten (1977), p. 368</ref>. Although the attribution to "Negi Satsuki Maro" in 768 is a fictional colophon, research by [[Mikannagi Kiyotada]] revealed that the text was based on the ancient records of Ise Jingū, such as the *Daijingū Honki*, and synthesized with the ancient text *Daidō Honki*<ref name="Ōsumi, 1977, p. 368"/>.

