Another oracle, "Return to the origin, and align yourself with the fundamental essence," conveys the idea of renewal through recognizing and restoring one’s connection to the source, a concept known as ''Motomoto Honhon.'' This philosophy resonates with the rituals of the {{ill|Shikinen Sengu|ja|式年遷宮|12=draft}}.<ref name="SakamotoIshii2011p55">Sakamoto Koremaru & Ishii Kenji, ''Prestep Shintōgaku,'' Kōbundō, 2011, p. 55.</ref>

== Research History ==

Empirical research on the ''Shinto Gobusho'' began with the Edo-period scholar {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|12=draft}} in ''Gobusho Setsuben'' (1736). Yukikazu criticized ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' as the latest among the ''Gobusho,'' claiming it was a medieval fabrication by {{ill|Outer Shrine|ja|外宮|12=draft}} priests.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/> However, later scholars such as {{ill|Motoori Norinaga|ja|本居宣長|12=draft}} recognized the inclusion of ancient {{ill|Ise traditions|ja|伊勢伝承|12=draft}} in the text. Further analysis by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|12=draft}} demonstrated its basis in ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|12=draft}}.'' Postwar research by scholars like {{ill|Okada Yoneo|ja|岡田米男|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishida Osamu|ja|西田長男|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|12=draft}} further refined understanding of the text’s origins and its incorporation of ancient traditions.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

