[[sn:Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki]]
[[ja:倭姫命世記]]

{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki}}

'''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki''' (倭姫命世記) is a text believed to have been compiled in the mid-{{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Within ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki,'' it is stated that the work was composed in the second year of {{ill|Jingokeiun|ja|神護景雲|12=draft|12=draft}} (768) by "Nenge Mayumaro." However, it is widely believed to have been compiled during the mid-{{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="#1">{{Cite web|title=倭姫命世記|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/倭姫命世記-649457|publisher=コトバンク}}</ref> It is one of the five foundational texts of {{ill|Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Shinto Gobusho|ja|神道五部書|12=draft|12=draft}}. The work records the traditions of {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}, identified in the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}'' and ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'' as the daughter of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, journeying across various regions with the deity {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft|12=draft}} before finally enshrining her at {{ill|Ise Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/detail/54.html|title=倭姫命世記|publisher=愛知県立図書館デジタルライブラリー}}</ref><ref name="#1"/> The text also strongly asserts the doctrines of {{ill|Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="Osumi1977p367">[[Kazuo Ōsumi]], ''Chūsei Shintō-ron'' (中世神道論), Iwanami Shoten, 1977, p. 367.</ref>

== Composition ==

The legends of ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' are closely related to the expansion of {{ill|Ise Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}’s {{ill|manors|ja|荘園|12=draft|12=draft}} (shōen) called ''Mikuriya'' throughout various regions from the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}} and the spread of Ise faith by lower-Ranking priests called ''Oshi'' after the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="#2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bunka.pref.mie.lg.jp/saiku/hyakuwa/journal.asp?record=23|title=罪作りだよ？『倭姫命世紀』|publisher=斎宮歴史博物館}}</ref> Scholars such as {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|12=draft|12=draft}} have attributed its compilation to {{ill|Watarai Yukitada|ja|度会行忠|12=draft|12=draft}}, though {{ill|Kamada Junichi|ja|鎌田純一|12=draft|12=draft}} suggested that it had already been composed before Yukitada’s time.<ref name="Ban1993p5-6">Ban Gojirō, ''Kaidai,'' ''Shintō Taikei: Ise Shintō (Vol. 1)'', Shintō Taikei Hensankai, 1993, pp. 5–6.</ref> Among the medieval "Shinto Gobusho," ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' is thought to have been composed relatively early, following ''{{ill|Hōki Honki|ja|宝基本紀|12=draft|12=draft}},'' and further developing the philosophical ideas of that text.<ref name="Itō2012p99">[[Satoshi Itō]], ''Shintō to wa nani ka'' (神道とは何か), Chūō Kōron Shinsha, 2012, p. 99.</ref><ref name="Osumi1977p368">Kazuo Ōsumi, ''Chūsei Shintō-ron'', Iwanami Shoten, 1977, p. 368.</ref> While the attribution to Nenge Mayumaro in Jingokeiun 2 is fictional, studies by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|12=draft|12=draft}} have revealed that the text was based on ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|12=draft|12=draft}},'' an ancient document of {{ill|Ise Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, and incorporated traditional legends of the shrine.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

Its literary style combines elements of the {{ill|Senmyō|ja|宣命体|Senmyō=Senmyō|lt=Senmyō-gata|12=draft|12=draft}} style but is not entirely consistent. The latter sections are predominantly written in a pure {{ill|kanbun|ja|漢文|12=draft|12=draft}} style with few annotations, blending classical and Kamakura-period language.<ref name="Nakamura2012p441">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū: Fukkun to Dokkai,'' Shintensha, 2012, p. 441.</ref><ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū,'' pp. 2–3.</ref> The use of classical Senmyō style is considered an archaic embellishment to give the impression of antiquity.<ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3"/>

Legends of {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}} are widely recognized, and places said to have been her temporary palaces are scattered across {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|ja|岐阜県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="#2"/>

== Doctrine ==

''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' emphasizes {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft|12=draft}} philosophy alongside the narrative of the enshrinement of {{ill|Kōtai Jingu|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} by {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="Osumi1977p367"/> The text records that shortly before her passing in the 23rd year of {{ill|Emperor Yūryaku|ja|雄略天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, Yamatohime-no-Mikoto delivered a divine oracle. It describes the human heart as a divine spirit, or "Shinjin," emphasizing that humans must live in a state of "Seichoku" (正直, honesty) and "Seijō" (清浄, purity).<ref name="KaifuMitsuhashi2018p105-107">Kaifu Yawotome & Mitsuhashi Ken, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto-sama no Monogatari,'' Fuyōsha International, 2018, pp. 105–107.</ref> 

Another oracle, "Return to the origin, and align yourself with the fundamental essence," conveys the idea of renewal through recognizing and restoring one’s connection to the source, a concept known as ''Motomoto Honhon.'' This philosophy resonates with the rituals of the {{ill|Shikinen Sengu|ja|式年遷宮|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="SakamotoIshii2011p55">Sakamoto Koremaru & Ishii Kenji, ''Prestep Shintōgaku,'' Kōbundō, 2011, p. 55.</ref>

== Research History ==

Empirical research on the ''Shinto Gobusho'' began with the Edo-period scholar {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|12=draft|12=draft}} in ''Gobusho Setsuben'' (1736). Yukikazu criticized ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' as the latest among the ''Gobusho,'' claiming it was a medieval fabrication by {{ill|Outer Shrine|ja|外宮|12=draft|12=draft}} priests.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/> However, later scholars such as {{ill|Motoori Norinaga|ja|本居宣長|12=draft|12=draft}} recognized the inclusion of ancient {{ill|Ise traditions|ja|伊勢伝承|12=draft|12=draft}} in the text. Further analysis by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|12=draft|12=draft}} demonstrated its basis in ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}.'' Postwar research by scholars like {{ill|Okada Yoneo|ja|岡田米男|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishida Osamu|ja|西田長男|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|12=draft|12=draft}} further refined understanding of the text’s origins and its incorporation of ancient traditions.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

