Its literary style combines elements of the {{ill|Senmyō|ja|宣命体|Senmyō=Senmyō|lt=Senmyō-gata|qq=draft|qq=draft}} style but is not entirely consistent. The latter sections are predominantly written in a pure {{ill|kanbun|ja|漢文|qq=draft|qq=draft}} style with few annotations, blending classical and Kamakura-period language.<ref name="Nakamura2012p441">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū: Fukkun to Dokkai,'' Shintensha, 2012, p. 441.</ref><ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū,'' pp. 2–3.</ref> The use of classical Senmyō style is considered an archaic embellishment to give the impression of antiquity.<ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3"/>

Legends of {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are widely recognized, and places said to have been her temporary palaces are scattered across {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|ja|岐阜県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="#2"/>

== Doctrine ==

''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' emphasizes {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} philosophy alongside the narrative of the enshrinement of {{ill|Kōtai Jingu|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} by {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Osumi1977p367"/> The text records that shortly before her passing in the 23rd year of {{ill|Emperor Yūryaku|ja|雄略天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Yamatohime-no-Mikoto delivered a divine oracle. It describes the human heart as a divine spirit, or "Shinjin," emphasizing that humans must live in a state of "Seichoku" (正直, honesty) and "Seijō" (清浄, purity).<ref name="KaifuMitsuhashi2018p105-107">Kaifu Yawotome & Mitsuhashi Ken, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto-sama no Monogatari,'' Fuyōsha International, 2018, pp. 105–107.</ref> 

Another oracle, "Return to the origin, and align yourself with the fundamental essence," conveys the idea of renewal through recognizing and restoring one’s connection to the source, a concept known as ''Motomoto Honhon.'' This philosophy resonates with the rituals of the {{ill|Shikinen Sengu|ja|式年遷宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="SakamotoIshii2011p55">Sakamoto Koremaru & Ishii Kenji, ''Prestep Shintōgaku,'' Kōbundō, 2011, p. 55.</ref>

== Research History ==

Empirical research on the ''Shinto Gobusho'' began with the Edo-period scholar {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in ''Gobusho Setsuben'' (1736). Yukikazu criticized ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' as the latest among the ''Gobusho,'' claiming it was a medieval fabrication by {{ill|Outer Shrine|ja|外宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} priests.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/> However, later scholars such as {{ill|Motoori Norinaga|ja|本居宣長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} recognized the inclusion of ancient {{ill|Ise traditions|ja|伊勢伝承|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the text. Further analysis by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|qq=draft|qq=draft}} demonstrated its basis in ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.'' Postwar research by scholars like {{ill|Okada Yoneo|ja|岡田米男|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nishida Osamu|ja|西田長男|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|qq=draft|qq=draft}} further refined understanding of the text’s origins and its incorporation of ancient traditions.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

