[[sn:Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki]]
[[ja:倭姫命世記]]

'''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki''' (倭姫命世記) is a text believed to have been compiled in the mid-[[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]].

Within ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki,'' it is stated that the work was composed in the second year of [[:en:Jingo-keiun|Jingokeiun]] (768) by "Nenge Mayumaro." However, it is widely believed to have been compiled during the mid-[[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]].<ref name="#1">{{Cite web|title=倭姫命世記|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/倭姫命世記-649457|publisher=コトバンク}}</ref> It is one of the five foundational texts of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Shinto|qq=}}, the {{ill|Shintō Gobusho|lt=Shintō Gobusho|lt=Shinto Gobusho|ja|神道五部書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto Gobusho|qq=}}. The work records the traditions of [[:en:Yamatohime-no-mikoto|Yamatohime-no-mikoto]], identified in the ''[[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]'' and ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' as the daughter of [[:en:Emperor Suinin|Emperor Suinin]], journeying across various regions with the deity [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]] before finally enshrining her at [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/detail/54.html|title=倭姫命世記|publisher=愛知県立図書館デジタルライブラリー}}</ref><ref name="#1"/> The text also strongly asserts the doctrines of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Shinto|qq=}}.<ref name="Osumi1977p367">[[Kazuo Ōsumi]], ''Chūsei Shintō-ron'' (中世神道論), Iwanami Shoten, 1977, p. 367.</ref>

== Composition ==

The legends of ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' are closely related to the expansion of [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Shrine]]’s [[:en:Manorialism|manors]] (shōen) called ''Mikuriya'' throughout various regions from the late [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]] and the spread of Ise faith by lower-Ranking priests called ''Oshi'' after the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]].<ref name="#2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bunka.pref.mie.lg.jp/saiku/hyakuwa/journal.asp?record=23|title=罪作りだよ？『倭姫命世紀』|publisher=斎宮歴史博物館}}</ref> Scholars such as {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kubota Osamu|qq=}} have attributed its compilation to {{ill|Watarai Yukitada|ja|度会行忠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai Yukitada|qq=}}, though {{ill|Kamada Junichi|ja|鎌田純一|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamada Junichi|qq=}} suggested that it had already been composed before Yukitada’s time.<ref name="Ban1993p5-6">Ban Gojirō, ''Kaidai,'' ''Shintō Taikei: Ise Shintō (Vol. 1)'', Shintō Taikei Hensankai, 1993, pp. 5–6.</ref> Among the medieval "Shinto Gobusho," ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' is thought to have been composed relatively early, following ''{{ill|Hōki Honki|ja|宝基本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōki Honki|qq=}},'' and further developing the philosophical ideas of that text.<ref name="Itō2012p99">[[Satoshi Itō]], ''Shintō to wa nani ka'' (神道とは何か), Chūō Kōron Shinsha, 2012, p. 99.</ref><ref name="Osumi1977p368">Kazuo Ōsumi, ''Chūsei Shintō-ron'', Iwanami Shoten, 1977, p. 368.</ref> While the attribution to Nenge Mayumaro in Jingokeiun 2 is fictional, studies by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikannagi Kiyonao|qq=}} have revealed that the text was based on ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijingū Honki|qq=}},'' an ancient document of [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Shrine]], and incorporated traditional legends of the shrine.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

Its literary style combines elements of the {{ill|Senmyō|ja|宣命体|Senmyō=Senmyō|lt=Senmyō-gata|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senmyō|qq=}} style but is not entirely consistent. The latter sections are predominantly written in a pure [[:en:Classical Chinese|kanbun]] style with few annotations, blending classical and Kamakura-period language.<ref name="Nakamura2012p441">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū: Fukkun to Dokkai,'' Shintensha, 2012, p. 441.</ref><ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3">Nakamura Yukihiro, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki Kenkyū,'' pp. 2–3.</ref> The use of classical Senmyō style is considered an archaic embellishment to give the impression of antiquity.<ref name="Nakamura2012p2-3"/>

Legends of [[:en:Yamatohime-no-mikoto|Yamatohime-no-mikoto]] are widely recognized, and places said to have been her temporary palaces are scattered across [[:en:Gifu Prefecture|Gifu Prefecture]], [[:en:Shiga Prefecture|Shiga Prefecture]], and [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]].<ref name="#2"/>

== Doctrine ==

''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' emphasizes [[:en:Shinto|Shinto]] philosophy alongside the narrative of the enshrinement of {{ill|Kōtai Jingu|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingu|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingū|qq=}} by [[:en:Yamatohime-no-mikoto|Yamatohime-no-mikoto]].<ref name="Osumi1977p367"/> The text records that shortly before her passing in the 23rd year of [[:en:Emperor Yūryaku|Emperor Yūryaku]], Yamatohime-no-Mikoto delivered a divine oracle. It describes the human heart as a divine spirit, or "Shinjin," emphasizing that humans must live in a state of "Seichoku" (正直, honesty) and "Seijō" (清浄, purity).<ref name="KaifuMitsuhashi2018p105-107">Kaifu Yawotome & Mitsuhashi Ken, ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto-sama no Monogatari,'' Fuyōsha International, 2018, pp. 105–107.</ref> 

Another oracle, "Return to the origin, and align yourself with the fundamental essence," conveys the idea of renewal through recognizing and restoring one’s connection to the source, a concept known as ''Motomoto Honhon.'' This philosophy resonates with the rituals of the {{ill|Jingū Shikinen Sengū|lt=Jingū Shikinen Sengū|lt=Shikinen Sengu|ja|式年遷宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinen Sengu|qq=}}.<ref name="SakamotoIshii2011p55">Sakamoto Koremaru & Ishii Kenji, ''Prestep Shintōgaku,'' Kōbundō, 2011, p. 55.</ref>

== Research History ==

Empirical research on the ''Shinto Gobusho'' began with the Edo-period scholar {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimi Yukikazu|qq=}} in ''Gobusho Setsuben'' (1736). Yukikazu criticized ''Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki'' as the latest among the ''Gobusho,'' claiming it was a medieval fabrication by {{ill|Kōtai Jingū|lt=Kōtai Jingū|lt=Outer Shrine|ja|外宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Outer Shrine|qq=}} priests.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/> However, later scholars such as [[:en:Motoori Norinaga|Motoori Norinaga]] recognized the inclusion of ancient {{ill|Ise traditions|ja|伊勢伝承|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise traditions|qq=}} in the text. Further analysis by {{ill|Mikannagi Kiyonao|ja|御巫清直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikannagi Kiyonao|qq=}} demonstrated its basis in ''{{ill|Daijingū Honki|ja|太神宮本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijingū Honki|qq=}}.'' Postwar research by scholars like {{ill|Okada Yoneo|ja|岡田米男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okada Yoneo|qq=}}, {{ill|Nishida Osamu|ja|西田長男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishida Osamu|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kubota Osamu|ja|久保田収|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kubota Osamu|qq=}} further refined understanding of the text’s origins and its incorporation of ancient traditions.<ref name="Osumi1977p368"/>

